# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kubernetes-controllers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] In robotics and automation, a *control loop* is a non-terminating loop that regulates the state of a system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Here is one example of a control loop: a thermostat in a room.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] When you set the temperature, that's telling the thermostat about your *desired state*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The actual room temperature is the *current state*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The thermostat acts to bring the current state closer to the desired state, by turning equipment on or off.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] , then make or request changes where needed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Each controller tries to move the current cluster state closer to the desired state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] A controller tracks at least one Kubernetes resource type.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] These objects have a spec field that represents the desired state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The controller(s) for that resource are responsible for making the current state come closer to that desired state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The controller might carry the action out itself; more commonly, in Kubernetes, a controller will send messages to the API server that have useful side effects.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The Job controller is an example of a Kubernetes built-in controller.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Built-in controllers manage state by interacting with the cluster API server.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Job is a Kubernetes resource that runs a Pod, or perhaps several Pods, to carry out a task and then stop.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] (Once scheduled, Pod objects become part of the desired state for a kubelet).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] When the Job controller sees a new task it makes sure that, somewhere in your cluster, the kubelets on a set of Nodes are running the right number of Pods to get the work done.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The Job controller does not run any Pods or containers itself.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Instead, the Job controller tells the API server to create or remove Pods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Other components in the control plane act on the new information (there are new Pods to schedule and run), and eventually the work is done.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] After you create a new Job, the desired state is for that Job to be completed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The Job controller makes the current state for that Job be nearer to your desired state: creating Pods that do the work you wanted for that Job, so that the Job is closer to completion.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Controllers also update the objects that configure them.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] For example: once the work is done for a Job, the Job controller updates that Job object to mark it `Finished`.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] (This is a bit like how some thermostats turn a light off to indicate that your room is now at the temperature you set).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] In contrast with Job, some controllers need to make changes to things outside of your cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] For example, if you use a control loop to make sure there are enough Nodes in your cluster, then that controller needs something outside the current cluster to set up new Nodes when needed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Controllers that interact with external state find their desired state from the API server, then communicate directly with an external system to bring the current state closer in line.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The important point here is that the controller makes some changes to bring about your desired state, and then reports the current state back to your cluster's API server.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Other control loops can observe that reported data and take their own actions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] In the thermostat example, if the room is very cold then a different controller might also turn on a frost protection heater.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] With Kubernetes clusters, the control plane indirectly works with IP address management tools, storage services, cloud provider APIs, and other services by extending Kubernetes to implement that.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Kubernetes takes a cloud-native view of systems, and is able to handle constant change.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Your cluster could be changing at any point as work happens and control loops automatically fix failures.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] This means that, potentially, your cluster never reaches a stable state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] As long as the controllers for your cluster are running and able to make useful changes, it doesn't matter if the overall state is stable or not.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] As a tenet of its design, Kubernetes uses lots of controllers that each manage a particular aspect of cluster state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Most commonly, a particular control loop (controller) uses one kind of resource as its desired state, and has a different kind of resource that it manages to make that desired state happen.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] For example, a controller for Jobs tracks Job objects (to discover new work) and Pod objects (to run the Jobs, and then to see when the work is finished).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] In this case something else creates the Jobs, whereas the Job controller creates Pods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] It's useful to have simple controllers rather than one, monolithic set of control loops that are interlinked.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Controllers can fail, so Kubernetes is designed to allow for that.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] There can be several controllers that create or update the same kind of object.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Behind the scenes, Kubernetes controllers make sure that they only pay attention to the resources linked to their controlling resource.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] For example, you can have Deployments and Jobs; these both create Pods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The Job controller does not delete the Pods that your Deployment created, because there is information (labels) the controllers can use to tell those Pods apart.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Kubernetes comes with a set of built-in controllers that run inside the kube-controller-manager.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] These built-in controllers provide important core behaviors.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] The Deployment controller and Job controller are examples of controllers that come as part of Kubernetes itself ("built-in" controllers).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Kubernetes lets you run a resilient control plane, so that if any of the built-in controllers were to fail, another part of the control plane will take over the work.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] You can find controllers that run outside the control plane, to extend Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] Or, if you want, you can write a new controller yourself.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] You can run your own controller as a set of Pods, or externally to Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/architecture-controller] What fits best will depend on what that particular controller does.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] A **control loop** is the fundamental building block of control systems in general and industrial control systems in particular.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] It consists of the process sensor, the controller function, and the final control element (FCE) which controls the process necessary to automatically adjust the value of a measured process variable (PV) to equal the value of a desired set-point (SP).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] There are two common classes of control loop: open loop and closed loop.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] An example of a control system is a car's cruise control, which is a device designed to maintain vehicle speed at a constant *desired* or *reference* speed provided by the driver.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The *controller* is the cruise control, the *plant* is the car, and the *system* is the car and the cruise control.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The system output is the car's speed, and the control itself is the engine's throttle position which determines how much power the engine delivers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] A primitive way to implement cruise control is simply to lock the throttle position when the driver engages cruise control.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] However, if the cruise control is engaged on a stretch of non-flat road, then the car will travel slower going uphill and faster when going downhill.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In a *closed-loop control system*, data from a sensor monitoring the car's speed (the system output) enters a controller which continuously compares the quantity representing the speed with the reference quantity representing the desired speed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The difference, called the error, determines the throttle position (the control).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The result is to match the car's speed to the reference speed (maintain the desired system output).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] Now, when the car goes uphill, the difference between the input (the sensed speed) and the reference continuously determines the throttle position.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] As the sensed speed drops below the reference, the difference increases, the throttle opens, and engine power increases, speeding up the vehicle.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In this way, the controller dynamically counteracts changes to the car's speed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The central idea of these control systems is the *feedback loop*, the controller affects the system output, which in turn is measured and fed back to the controller.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The accompanying diagram shows a control loop with a single PV input, a control function, and the control output (CO) which modulates the action of the final control element (FCE) to alter the value of the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In this example, a flow control loop is shown, but can be level, temperature, or any one of many process parameters which need to be controlled.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The control function shown is an "intermediate type" such as a PID controller which means it can generate a full range of output signals anywhere between 0-100%, rather than just an on/off signal.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In this example, the value of the PV is always the same as the MV, as they are in series in the pipeline.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] However, if the feed from the valve was to a tank, and the controller function was to control the level using the fill valve, the PV would be the tank level, and the MV would be the flow to the tank.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The controller function can be a discrete controller or a function block in a computerised control system such as a distributed control system or a programmable logic controller.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In all cases, a control loop diagram is a very convenient and useful way of representing the control function and its interaction with plant.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] In practice at a process control level, control loops are normally abbreviated using standard symbols in a Piping and instrumentation diagram, which shows all elements of the process measurement and control based on a process flow diagram.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] At a detailed level, the control loop connection diagram is created to show the electrical and pneumatic connections.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] This greatly aids diagnostics and repair, as all the connections for a single control function are on one diagram.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] To aid unique identification of equipment, each loop and its elements are identified by a "tagging" system and each element has a unique tag identification.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] Based on the standards ANSI/ISA S5.1 and ISO 14617-6, the identifications consist of up to 5 letters.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The first identification letter is for the measured value, the second is a modifier, 3rd indicates the passive/readout function, 4th - active/output function, and the 5th is the function modifier.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] This is followed by loop number, which is unique to that loop.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] For instance, FIC045 means it is the Flow Indicating Controller in control loop 045.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] This is also known as the "tag" identifier of the field device, which is normally given to the location and function of the instrument.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-loop] The same loop may have FT045 - which is the flow transmitter in the same loop.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] To do this, a **controller** with the requisite corrective behavior is required.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This controller monitors the controlled process variable (PV), and compares it with the reference or set point (SP).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The difference between actual and desired value of the process variable, called the *error* signal, or SP-PV error, is applied as feedback to generate a control action to bring the controlled process variable to the same value as the set point.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Other aspects which are also studied are controllability and observability.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control theory is used in control system engineering to design automation that have revolutionized manufacturing, aircraft, communications and other industries, and created new fields such as robotics.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Extensive use is usually made of a diagrammatic style known as the block diagram.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In it the transfer function, also known as the system function or network function, is a mathematical model of the relation between the input and output based on the differential equations describing the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control theory dates from the 19th century, when the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control theory was further advanced by Edward Routh in 1874, Charles Sturm and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, who all contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria; and from 1922 onwards, the development of PID control theory by Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Although the most direct application of mathematical control theory is its use in control systems engineering (dealing with process control systems for robotics and industry), control theory is routinely applied to problems both the natural and behavioral sciences.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] As the general theory of feedback systems, control theory is useful wherever feedback occurs, making it important to fields like economics, operations research, and the life sciences.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Although control systems of various types date back to antiquity, a more formal analysis of the field began with a dynamics analysis of the centrifugal governor, conducted by the physicist James Clerk Maxwell in 1868, entitled *On Governors*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A centrifugal governor was already used to regulate the velocity of windmills.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Maxwell described and analyzed the phenomenon of self-oscillation, in which lags in the system may lead to overcompensation and unstable behavior.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This generated a flurry of interest in the topic, during which Maxwell's classmate, Edward John Routh, abstracted Maxwell's results for the general class of linear systems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Independently, Adolf Hurwitz analyzed system stability using differential equations in 1877, resulting in what is now known as the Routh–Hurwitz theorem.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A notable application of dynamic control was in the area of crewed flight.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The Wright brothers made their first successful test flights on December 17, 1903, and were distinguished by their ability to control their flights for substantial periods (more so than the ability to produce lift from an airfoil, which was known).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Continuous, reliable control of the airplane was necessary for flights lasting longer than a few seconds.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] By World War II, control theory was becoming an important area of research.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control systems, and applied the bang-bang principle to the development of automatic flight control equipment for aircraft.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Other areas of application for discontinuous controls included fire-control systems, guidance systems and electronics.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Sometimes, mechanical methods are used to improve the stability of systems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] For example, ship stabilizers are fins mounted beneath the waterline and emerging laterally.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In contemporary vessels, they may be gyroscopically controlled active fins, which have the capacity to change their angle of attack to counteract roll caused by wind or waves acting on the ship.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The Space Race also depended on accurate spacecraft control, and control theory has also seen an increasing use in fields such as economics and artificial intelligence.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Here, one might say that the goal is to find an internal model that obeys the good regulator theorem.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] So, for example, in economics, the more accurately a (stock or commodities) trading model represents the actions of the market, the more easily it can control that market (and extract "useful work" (profits) from it).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These last two examples take the narrow historical interpretation of control theory as a set of differential equations modeling and regulating kinetic motion, and broaden it into a vast generalization of a regulator interacting with a plant.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A closed-loop controller or feedback controller is a control loop which incorporates feedback, in contrast to an *open-loop controller* or *non-feedback controller*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A closed-loop controller uses feedback to control states or outputs of a dynamical system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In the case of linear feedback systems, a control loop including sensors, control algorithms, and actuators is arranged in an attempt to regulate a variable at a setpoint (SP).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] An everyday example is the cruise control on a road vehicle; where external influences such as hills would cause speed changes, and the driver has the ability to alter the desired set speed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The PID algorithm in the controller restores the actual speed to the desired speed in an optimum way, with minimal delay or overshoot, by controlling the power output of the vehicle's engine.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control systems that include some sensing of the results they are trying to achieve are making use of feedback and can adapt to varying circumstances to some extent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Open-loop control systems do not make use of feedback, and run only in pre-arranged ways.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In some systems, closed-loop and open-loop control are used simultaneously.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In such systems, the open-loop control is termed *feedforward* and serves to further improve reference tracking performance.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A common closed-loop controller architecture is the PID controller.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In contrast to the frequency-domain analysis of the classical control theory, modern control theory utilizes the time-domain state space representation, a mathematical model of a physical system as a set of input, output and state variables related by first-order differential equations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] To abstract from the number of inputs, outputs, and states, the variables are expressed as vectors and the differential and algebraic equations are written in matrix form (the latter only being possible when the dynamical system is linear).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The state space representation (also known as the "time-domain approach") provides a convenient and compact way to model and analyze systems with multiple inputs and outputs.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] With inputs and outputs, we would otherwise have to write down Laplace transforms to encode all the information about a system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Unlike the frequency domain approach, the use of the state-space representation is not limited to systems with linear components and zero initial conditions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] "State space" refers to the space whose axes are the state variables.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The state of the system can be represented as a point within that space.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control systems can be divided into different categories depending on the number of inputs and outputs.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The scope of classical control theory is limited to single-input and single-output (SISO) system design, except when analyzing for disturbance rejection using a second input.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The system analysis is carried out in the time domain using differential equations, in the complex-s domain with the Laplace transform, or in the frequency domain by transforming from the complex-s domain.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Many systems may be assumed to have a second order and single variable system response in the time domain.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A controller designed using classical theory often requires on-site tuning due to incorrect design approximations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Yet, due to the easier physical implementation of classical controller designs as compared to systems designed using modern control theory, these controllers are preferred in most industrial applications.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The most common controllers designed using classical control theory are PID controllers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A less common implementation may include either or both a Lead or Lag filter.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The ultimate end goal is to meet requirements typically provided in the time-domain called the step response, or at times in the frequency domain called the open-loop response.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The step response characteristics applied in a specification are typically percent overshoot, settling time, etc.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The open-loop response characteristics applied in a specification are typically Gain and Phase margin and bandwidth.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These characteristics may be evaluated through simulation including a dynamic model of the system under control coupled with the compensation model.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Modern control theory is carried out in the state space, and can deal with multiple-input and multiple-output (MIMO) systems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This overcomes the limitations of classical control theory in more sophisticated design problems, such as fighter aircraft control, with the limitation that no frequency domain analysis is possible.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In modern design, a system is represented to the greatest advantage as a set of decoupled first order differential equations defined using state variables.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Nonlinear, multivariable, adaptive and robust control theories come under this division.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Being fairly new, modern control theory has many areas yet to be explored.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Kálmán and Aleksandr Lyapunov are well known among the people who have shaped modern control theory.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The *stability* of a general dynamical system with no input can be described with Lyapunov stability criteria.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] For simplicity, the following descriptions focus on continuous-time and discrete-time **linear systems**.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Mathematically, this means that for a causal linear system to be stable all of the poles of its transfer function must have negative-real values, i.e. the real part of each pole must be less than zero.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The difference between the two cases is simply due to the traditional method of plotting continuous time versus discrete time transfer functions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The continuous Laplace transform is in Cartesian coordinates where the x axis is the real axis and the discrete Z-transform is in circular coordinates where the $\rho$ axis is the real axis.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] When the appropriate conditions above are satisfied a system is said to be asymptotically stable; the variables of an asymptotically stable control system always decrease from their initial value and do not show permanent oscillations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Permanent oscillations occur when a pole has a real part exactly equal to zero (in the continuous time case) or a modulus equal to one (in the discrete time case).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] If a simply stable system response neither decays nor grows over time, and has no oscillations, it is marginally stable; in this case the system transfer function has non-repeated poles at the complex plane origin (i.e. their real and complex component is zero in the continuous time case).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Oscillations are present when poles with real part equal to zero have an imaginary part not equal to zero.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] which has a pole in $z=0.5$ (zero imaginary part).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This system is BIBO (asymptotically) stable since the pole is *inside* the unit circle.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] which has a pole at $z=1.5$ and is not BIBO stable since the pole has a modulus strictly greater than one.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Numerous tools exist for the analysis of the poles of a system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These include graphical systems like the root locus, Bode plots or the Nyquist plots.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Mechanical changes can make equipment (and control systems) more stable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Sailors add ballast to improve the stability of ships.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Cruise ships use antiroll fins that extend transversely from the side of the ship for perhaps 30 feet (10 m) and are continuously rotated about their axes to develop forces that oppose the roll.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Controllability and observability are main issues in the analysis of a system before deciding the best control strategy to be applied, or whether it is even possible to control or stabilize the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Controllability is related to the possibility of forcing the system into a particular state by using an appropriate control signal.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, then no signal will ever be able to control the state.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] If a state is not controllable, but its dynamics are stable, then the state is termed *stabilizable*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Observability instead is related to the possibility of *observing*, through output measurements, the state of a system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] If a state is not observable, the controller will never be able to determine the behavior of an unobservable state and hence cannot use it to stabilize the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] However, similar to the stabilizability condition above, if a state cannot be observed it might still be detectable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] From a geometrical point of view, looking at the states of each variable of the system to be controlled, every "bad" state of these variables must be controllable and observable to ensure a good behavior in the closed-loop system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] That is, if one of the eigenvalues of the system is not both controllable and observable, this part of the dynamics will remain untouched in the closed-loop system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] If such an eigenvalue is not stable, the dynamics of this eigenvalue will be present in the closed-loop system which therefore will be unstable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Unobservable poles are not present in the transfer function realization of a state-space representation, which is why sometimes the latter is preferred in dynamical systems analysis.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Solutions to problems of an uncontrollable or unobservable system include adding actuators and sensors.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Several different control strategies have been devised in the past years.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These vary from extremely general ones (PID controller), to others devoted to very particular classes of systems (especially robotics or aircraft cruise control).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A control problem can have several specifications.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Stability, of course, is always present.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The controller must ensure that the closed-loop system is stable, regardless of the open-loop stability.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A poor choice of controller can even worsen the stability of the open-loop system, which must normally be avoided.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Sometimes it would be desired to obtain particular dynamics in the closed loop: i.e. that the poles have $Re[\lambda ]<-{\overline {\lambda }}$ , where ${\overline {\lambda }}$ is a fixed value strictly greater than zero, instead of simply asking that $Re[\lambda ]<0$ .
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Another typical specification is the rejection of a step disturbance; including an integrator in the open-loop chain (i.e. directly before the system under control) easily achieves this.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Other classes of disturbances need different types of sub-systems to be included.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Other "classical" control theory specifications regard the time-response of the closed-loop system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These include the rise time (the time needed by the control system to reach the desired value after a perturbation), peak overshoot (the highest value reached by the response before reaching the desired value) and others (settling time, quarter-decay).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Frequency domain specifications are usually related to robustness (see after).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Modern performance assessments use some variation of integrated tracking error (IAE, ISA, CQI).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A control system must always have some robustness property.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A robust controller is such that its properties do not change much if applied to a system slightly different from the mathematical one used for its synthesis.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This requirement is important, as no real physical system truly behaves like the series of differential equations used to represent it mathematically.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Typically a simpler mathematical model is chosen in order to simplify calculations, otherwise, the true system dynamics can be so complicated that a complete model is impossible.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The process of determining the equations that govern the model's dynamics is called system identification.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This can be done off-line: for example, executing a series of measures from which to calculate an approximated mathematical model, typically its transfer function or matrix.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Such identification from the output, however, cannot take account of unobservable dynamics.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Sometimes the model is built directly starting from known physical equations, for example, in the case of a mass-spring-damper system we know that $m{\ddot {x}}(t)=-Kx(t)-\mathrm {B} {\dot {x}}(t)$ .
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Some advanced control techniques include an "on-line" identification process (see later).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The parameters of the model are calculated ("identified") while the controller itself is running.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In this way, if a drastic variation of the parameters ensues, for example, if the robot's arm releases a weight, the controller will adjust itself consequently in order to ensure the correct performance.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Analysis of the robustness of a SISO (single input single output) control system can be performed in the frequency domain, considering the system's transfer function and using Nyquist and Bode diagrams.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Topics include gain and phase margin and amplitude margin.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] For MIMO (multi-input multi output) and, in general, more complicated control systems, one must consider the theoretical results devised for each control technique (see next section).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] I.e., if particular robustness qualities are needed, the engineer must shift their attention to a control technique by including these qualities in its properties.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A particular robustness issue is the requirement for a control system to perform properly in the presence of input and state constraints.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In the physical world every signal is limited.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] It could happen that a controller will send control signals that cannot be followed by the physical system, for example, trying to rotate a valve at excessive speed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] This can produce undesired behavior of the closed-loop system, or even damage or break actuators or other subsystems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Specific control techniques are available to solve the problem: model predictive control (see later), and anti-wind up systems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The latter consists of an additional control block that ensures that the control signal never exceeds a given threshold.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] For MIMO systems, pole placement can be performed mathematically using a state space representation of the open-loop system and calculating a feedback matrix assigning poles in the desired positions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In complicated systems this can require computer-assisted calculation capabilities, and cannot always ensure robustness.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Furthermore, all system states are not in general measured and so observers must be included and incorporated in pole placement design.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Processes in industries like robotics and the aerospace industry typically have strong nonlinear dynamics.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] In control theory it is sometimes possible to linearize such classes of systems and apply linear techniques, but in many cases it can be necessary to devise from scratch theories permitting control of nonlinear systems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] These, e.g., feedback linearization, backstepping, sliding mode control, trajectory linearization control normally take advantage of results based on Lyapunov's theory.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Differential geometry has been widely used as a tool for generalizing well-known linear control concepts to the nonlinear case, as well as showing the subtleties that make it a more challenging problem.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Control theory has also been used to decipher the neural mechanism that directs cognitive states.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] When the system is controlled by multiple controllers, the problem is one of decentralized control.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Decentralization is helpful in many ways, for instance, it helps control systems to operate over a larger geographical area.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The agents in decentralized control systems can interact using communication channels and coordinate their actions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A stochastic control problem is one in which the evolution of the state variables is subjected to random shocks from outside the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] A deterministic control problem is not subject to external random shocks.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Every control system must guarantee first the stability of the closed-loop behavior.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] For linear systems, this can be obtained by directly placing the poles.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] Nonlinear control systems use specific theories (normally based on Aleksandr Lyapunov's Theory) to ensure stability without regard to the inner dynamics of the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/control-theory] The possibility to fulfill different specifications varies from the model considered and the control strategy chosen.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-controllers/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
